    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">The Freeps side, naturally, revolved around Gandalf&#39;s text and forearmed. Once you can stack Sauron on top of your draw deck regularly nothing can stop you. Even the relatively weak Galadriel can overwhelm Cave Trolls, Balrogs, and other giant Besiegers. Gil-galad wipes out other stuff, Glorfindel is strong, and Legs can pick off extra minions sitting around. It&#39;s a double-moving machine that generally kills every minion it faces, and with ease. <br />
<br />
I start Gandalf because I don&#39;t want to waste 4 or more cards slots on drawing him and for the very simple reason that I only have 1. It has worked out fine in every game I have played with it, I almost always draw an Elf in the starting hand, and even if I don&#39;t I can mulligan. Besides, Galadriel is an Elf and I can play Elrond, Troop, and the war band, which means the only companion I wouldn&#39;t be able to play right off the bat is Gil-galad. <br />
<br />
For the Shadow side, it&#39;s a basic Besieger deck. It&#39;s not particularly focuses, the main idea is to take control of sites, add threats, and then get Sauron out with a archery-protection minion. Which basically equals two dead companions. Even if you never play him, the big trolls which come down easily can stop the opponent&#39;s fellowship, letting you double ahead easily. This deck is still in the make, any suggestions would be greatly appreciated. Thanks. <br />
-Quickbeam  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
